alternatives.transcript: Hi there. Occasionally when you are using a Unix system you'll find files in a strange format. In other words the extension on them might be something like some file dot tar dot g z and you might say what is that? Well, it's basically a zipped up archive file. Basically it's just a zip file that you can extract and it gives you a folder or directory of files. So I just wanted to quickly go over how you would actually extract that from the command line. Here's how you do it, if you want to extract something like that you type tar which stands for tape archive, which is from back in the day when we actually used to use magnetic tape to store files and do backups and so forth. And you type tar and then the options dash XVF which stands for extract and V stands for show me all the files you've extracted and F stands for I'm about to give you a filename. And then, in this case I have one called assign zero dot tar dot g z and it will, untar the file for you. Okay? And if you wanna actually create a zip file like that, you could actually use the zip command, which is also pretty common. But if you wanna create this particular type of compressed file, you would type tar c z, which stands for compressed into a zipped form, and then v f, if you wanna see all the files again, and then a directory name and it will, oops, let's see tar dot g z, a directory, a filename and then a directory name and there you go. And that's how that's how a tar file tar command works. Thanks.
